WEBVTT

00:17.730 --> 00:21.936
Well, hey, a couple weeks ago, we started a brand new series here at the porch in the book of Genesis.

00:21.996 --> 00:25.000
It just felt fitting, you know, beginning of the year, beginning of the Bible.

00:25.200 --> 00:28.405
They just seem to be a match made in heaven, no pun intended.

00:28.445 --> 00:30.949
And so we've been journeying Genesis 1, Genesis 2.

00:30.989 --> 00:34.153
We had a conversation kind of in the middle there, whenever the snowstorm hit.

00:34.493 --> 00:39.601
And tonight, we are sitting in, what is one of the most iconic passages of scripture we are looking at Genesis 3?

00:39.961 --> 00:42.024
So if you have a Bible, you can go ahead and turn there with me.

00:42.445 --> 00:46.290
Right now, while you're doing that, I'll just lead off with a story, because I think

00:46.402 --> 00:49.865
Maybe my misery can set us up pretty well.

00:50.046 --> 00:51.747
Here's what happened a couple of weeks ago.

00:52.308 --> 00:53.649
Brooke and I, we had just finished dinner.

00:54.570 --> 00:57.053
And we were playing with cash right before bedtime.

00:57.113 --> 00:58.234
We were sitting in our sunroom.

00:58.254 --> 01:01.237
And so we're kind of closing the evening down.

01:01.257 --> 01:02.678
And so I get up and I go to the kitchen.

01:02.698 --> 01:03.379
I know there's some dishes.

01:03.419 --> 01:07.703
And so I start to make my way just to do some dishes before we go and we put the little baby boy to sleep.

01:07.743 --> 01:11.867
And as I'm walking into the kitchen, I step into a puddle of water.

01:12.988 --> 01:14.610
And it just occurred to me.

01:14.946 --> 01:16.828
Maybe it's a leak off of the fridge.

01:17.048 --> 01:19.170
Sometimes you get tap water and things spill.

01:19.230 --> 01:23.894
Maybe it's something off the dishwasher, pulling out plates or dishes and finding that stuff kind of leaves a mess.

01:23.934 --> 01:25.555
Maybe it was Cassius water cup.

01:25.956 --> 01:29.038
He has a tendency to just kind of throw that thing around and leave a mess wherever it falls.

01:29.479 --> 01:32.361
And so I step back to survey the damage of what am I really dealing with here?

01:32.381 --> 01:37.165
And as I take it all in, what I realize to my horror is it's way worse than I thought it was.

01:37.726 --> 01:39.908
Because it was not just a puddle of water.

01:39.928 --> 01:44.932
It was a pool of water streaming into our entryway from the

01:44.912 --> 01:47.615
where our guest bathroom is.

01:49.176 --> 01:57.685
And so I pull back the pocket door and I put on my slides and I begin to make my way into what is a damage zone.

01:57.705 --> 02:00.408
I mean, it is an absolute mess in here.

02:00.448 --> 02:02.911
And so I know my way around some things in the house.

02:02.971 --> 02:04.632
I'm kind of a DIY sort of guy.

02:04.652 --> 02:09.417
And yet one of the things that I do not claim to have any kind of fame with is plumbing.

02:09.557 --> 02:14.002
I know next to nothing about plumbing, but, and fellas if you don't know this,

02:14.146 --> 02:14.928
You need to learn it.

02:15.629 --> 02:21.483
You know to turn off the water behind the toilet should ever the toilet be overflowing.

02:21.503 --> 02:27.095
So I swiftly move and I grab the knob and I spin it righty-tidy which shuts down the water.

02:27.657 --> 02:31.886
And then I grab a pitcher and I start to drain it off into the sink.

02:31.906 --> 02:33.650
As I'm doing that, as I'm

02:33.826 --> 02:47.120
repairing what appears to be a broken situation, the situation only seems to break all the more because as I'm draining the water off into the sink, the toilet continues to overflow and I have no idea what's happening because in this moment I've already shut off the water.

02:47.761 --> 03:00.594
And yet, the water's spilling, I'm erasing and so I go and I grab not one but two pictures, I'm double fisting trying to get the water out of the toilet into the sink to keep my house from becoming an absolute blood zone.

03:00.738 --> 03:09.327
And yet, a moment comes where I realize I'm out of my depth, and so I do what no self-respecting husband does.

03:10.228 --> 03:12.089
I look at my wife and I ask her to call her father.

03:12.810 --> 03:28.626
And as she calls my father-in-law, and she's explaining to him what's happening in this moment, that I'm draining the water out, that the toilets continuing to overflow, that I'm racing around, and she just says to him, hey, we don't know what's wrong, and I hear my father-in-law.

03:29.250 --> 03:30.852
laugh on the other end of the line.

03:30.872 --> 03:32.915
He goes, you're what's wrong.

03:32.975 --> 03:47.415
Because little did I know that we had a clog in the main kitchen clean out, which just means that all the water I was taking from the toilet and putting in the sink was just coming back up the toilet.

03:48.877 --> 03:54.105
So where I thought I was actually helping the situation, I was only hurting the situation.

03:55.447 --> 03:57.970
Now, why do I tell you that?

03:58.594 --> 04:01.500
the world has been asking that same question.

04:02.361 --> 04:06.128
What's gone wrong for centuries?

04:06.689 --> 04:19.674
And while they're not asking that question to deduce the problems of their bathroom, they are asking that question because they look at the landscape of life around and they realize something is wrong, things are not as they should be.

04:21.197 --> 04:21.778
You can look

04:22.338 --> 04:31.352
No matter who it is you speak to, whoever it is you reference, you can go back into the history books and you can see how people have tried to explain the origins of evil.

04:31.412 --> 04:32.935
You can look at Plato and Augustine.

04:32.955 --> 04:35.478
You can say that they would say evil wasn't an alternative good.

04:35.839 --> 04:37.161
It was a privation of good.

04:37.181 --> 04:38.423
It was the absence of good.

04:38.443 --> 04:48.018
You can go to Eastern religions like Hinduism and Buddhism and what you can learn is that evil isn't necessarily a rebellion against God as much as it's a confusion about the way

04:48.130 --> 05:18.116
the world works, you can go away from those Eastern religions and you can actually turn to dualism, which may be confusing to you, but it's actually a system of belief that many in our world that do not claim faith would ascribe to, that there's not just good, but there's bad, they are equal opposing forces, it's the idea of yin and yang, there's a light side and there's a dark side, there's two dogs and they're trying to get the better of one another, you can go and you can ask an evolutionist, hey, what is the origin of evil and what they would say is, oh, it's the result of survival instinct, you know, in order for someone to win, someone's gotta lose,

05:18.096 --> 05:30.116
If you wanted to go and you wanted to reference psychology, what you would see is that evil is the byproduct of negative circumstances that results in a negative emotional condition.

05:30.176 --> 05:33.542
It's where fear and insecurity and trauma come out of.

05:33.562 --> 05:35.345
That's what everything in the past would say.

05:35.565 --> 05:40.914
But if you wanted to zoom all the way here to the present and ask our current cultural moment, hey, what is it?

05:41.090 --> 05:43.012
that explains why things are the way they are.

05:43.112 --> 05:44.313
What in fact has gone wrong?

05:44.594 --> 05:47.076
You would see people present a variety of answers.

05:47.136 --> 05:51.420
It might be global warming or the industrial military complex and a lack of gun control.

05:51.541 --> 05:57.106
You might see that people would say it's political outrage, it's poor policy making.

05:57.366 --> 06:03.072
It's people divided over issues that ultimately do not matter at the cost of one another.

06:03.252 --> 06:06.776
You would see that it would be something in lines of an ever-evolving sexual revolution.

06:06.816 --> 06:08.978
It could be economic strain, rising,

06:09.506 --> 06:11.490
Cost of living, anybody say amen to that one?

06:11.530 --> 06:26.578
And if that's not enough, if the past and if the present isn't enough, you could make your way over to LA, you could look at Hollywood, you could see what they have to say because we have a thing for prequels all of a sudden, most of which are not very good.

06:28.354 --> 06:31.017
But we have this fascination to understand what's gone wrong.

06:31.057 --> 06:39.266
There's a reason that we need to not just live with episodes four, five, and six, but we got to go back to Star Wars episodes one, two, and three, so that way we can understand why Vader's voice sounds the way it does.

06:39.306 --> 06:45.493
There's a reason why the rings of power came out because people have questions about where Sauron came from.

06:45.533 --> 06:49.338
If you wanted to go even further, you could look at Wicked, one of the rare good ones.

06:49.638 --> 06:54.123
And what you can see is an explanation for why we have that Wicked Witch of the West.

06:55.224 --> 06:56.786
Everyone's asking what's gone wrong.

06:59.874 --> 07:00.815
You want to know what's gone wrong?

07:02.778 --> 07:03.059
We did.

07:06.524 --> 07:07.105
We went wrong.

07:08.647 --> 07:11.411
That's what the Bible tells us from page 3.

07:12.893 --> 07:19.963
In Genesis chapter 3, what we find is, yes, one of the most iconic Bible stories ever written.

07:20.184 --> 07:21.746
It is a story that

07:21.954 --> 07:28.404
not only Christians, but many non-Christians know because the story of Adam and Eve and the snake transcends time.

07:28.444 --> 07:36.657
It's one that resonates deeply with people because it provides an explanation for that question which we can find no good answer to.

07:38.019 --> 07:40.082
And yet here's the danger of this story.

07:40.386 --> 07:47.913
because it is so iconic, we have a tendency to approach it and bring all of our preconceptions with us.

07:48.314 --> 07:50.936
We walk into it and we don't take God on his terms.

07:51.177 --> 07:53.038
We take the story on someone else's terms.

07:53.059 --> 07:54.220
We don't listen to what he says.

07:54.460 --> 07:56.862
We recall what someone else has said in the past.

07:56.902 --> 08:00.646
I'm not telling you to just eject everything you've learned in the past.

08:00.666 --> 08:06.592
What I am saying is in this moment, it would serve you really well to read this story with fresh eyes alongside me.

08:06.652 --> 08:07.353
Does that sound good?

08:07.933 --> 08:08.754
I want you to,

08:08.866 --> 08:17.740
Look at this text and understand what it's actually saying, because we often misunderstand its meaning.

08:18.481 --> 08:20.364
And so we're just going to walk through it top to bottom.

08:21.226 --> 08:22.908
And I'm just going to explain to you what's happening.

08:23.630 --> 08:29.419
If you want to know what's gone wrong, and if you want to know, why do we go wrong?

08:30.721 --> 08:32.764
This is going to tell you.

08:32.784 --> 08:33.225
Verse one.

08:35.509 --> 08:36.370
Now the serpent

08:37.154 --> 08:42.601
was more crafty than any other beast of the field that the Lord God had made.

08:42.681 --> 08:48.069
He said to the woman, did God actually say, you shall not eat of any tree in the garden?

08:48.089 --> 08:55.018
And the woman said to the serpent, we may eat of the fruit of the trees in the garden, but God said you shall not eat of the fruit of the tree that is in the midst of the garden.

08:55.118 --> 08:56.340
Neither shall you touch it.

08:56.941 --> 08:57.882
Why lest you die?

08:58.963 --> 09:03.890
The first thing you need to know is things go wrong when we forget God's word.

09:05.314 --> 09:08.700
Things go wrong when we forget God's word.

09:08.962 --> 09:09.970
Like right out of the gate.

09:10.210 --> 09:16.578
Once we start reading through this story, there's a few things that pop up and should appear odd to us, should seem strange.

09:16.598 --> 09:22.185
Some signal players should be firing off into the atmosphere of your intellect.

09:22.265 --> 09:32.878
And the reason why is because we see, not just the woman, but we see the snake, both misrepresent what God has said in the stories that we've already read through Genesis 1 and Genesis 2.

09:33.178 --> 09:39.666
They do not correctly identify his commands, which begs the question then, what were God's commands?

09:40.034 --> 09:43.881
Well, Genesis 2, 16, 17 tells you, it's kind of a two-part command.

09:43.921 --> 09:53.058
The first command that God gave is, hey, you can eat of every tree in the garden, which is an amazing command.

09:53.959 --> 09:59.890
Because what it tells us is that God has looked upon Adam and Eve and he has said, hey, everything

10:00.386 --> 10:01.928
In the garden, it's fair game.

10:02.108 --> 10:04.391
Like you can get out there and you can take your pick.

10:04.591 --> 10:13.242
You can literally, you can enter into the proverbial grocery store and you can pick whatever you want off the shelves and it is not gonna actually add to your waistline.

10:13.262 --> 10:15.365
It's only going to lead to your joy.

10:15.525 --> 10:17.407
There's nothing here that you have to earn.

10:17.968 --> 10:19.850
Everything here is freely given.

10:19.910 --> 10:21.172
How amazing is that?

10:22.654 --> 10:23.415
Then there's the second part.

10:24.055 --> 10:26.098
The second part of the command is but,

10:26.786 --> 10:28.528
Just don't eat of one tree.

10:28.729 --> 10:31.552
Don't eat of the tree of the knowledge of good and evil.

10:31.873 --> 10:32.333
Why God?

10:32.714 --> 10:33.855
Because then you'll die.

10:34.236 --> 10:34.657
It's funny.

10:34.957 --> 10:43.809
We read that command and what we often hear is God say, but do not eat of the tree of the knowledge of good and evil.

10:45.030 --> 10:45.611
Or I'll kill you.

10:45.952 --> 10:47.754
That's not what actually is said here.

10:47.954 --> 10:49.957
What's said here is you'll die.

10:50.458 --> 10:55.624
God is not coming to us and saying, hey, you need to perform for my approval.

10:56.085 --> 10:56.786
That's not what he's saying.

10:56.866 --> 10:59.710
He's saying, no, joy is fully available to you.

10:59.730 --> 11:01.672
This is not about being performative.

11:01.692 --> 11:03.114
This is about being preventative.

11:03.395 --> 11:08.982
God is saying, hey, there is a whole world for you to enjoy all of this goodness that I have blessed you with.

11:09.322 --> 11:11.826
And yet there's one thing that will mess it up.

11:11.846 --> 11:12.767
So just don't do that.

11:14.529 --> 11:18.514
God's first command, it's not a prohibition to your joy.

11:19.976 --> 11:21.298
It's an invitation to joy.

11:22.018 --> 11:27.464
That's what God is inviting Adam and Eve into from the very beginning of the story.

11:27.765 --> 11:32.891
And yet, look at the way that the snake twists God's command.

11:34.432 --> 11:38.097
He says, did God actually say, you shall not eat of any tree in the garden?

11:39.338 --> 11:39.839
It's interesting.

11:39.859 --> 11:43.383
This is the way the enemy works.

11:43.403 --> 11:45.866
He doesn't need you to start by just denying God.

11:48.168 --> 11:49.650
He needs you to start by just doubting him.

11:50.594 --> 11:56.841
He just wants you to see that there might be something else available on the table.

11:56.901 --> 11:58.423
He doesn't need you to just reject God.

11:58.443 --> 11:59.644
That'd be a really hard sell.

11:59.944 --> 12:05.050
But because he's crafty, what he does is he looks and he says, no, you don't have to reject God, but I do want you to accept sin.

12:05.070 --> 12:12.739
He doesn't approach Eve with a smoking vial of poison, take and drink.

12:12.759 --> 12:13.500
You know, that's not what he does.

12:13.760 --> 12:14.681
He comes to her with what?

12:14.801 --> 12:17.804
Something that is delightful, that is pleasing to the eye.

12:18.325 --> 12:19.346
He comes in

12:19.586 --> 12:24.312
And he presents an option that appears satisfying.

12:25.393 --> 12:33.924
And what we see is that as she accepts sin, she takes the first step in forgetting God.

12:35.506 --> 12:37.789
Because we can just read her words and we can see that that's true.

12:38.049 --> 12:38.650
What are her words?

12:38.710 --> 12:43.717
Her words are, you shall not eat of the tree in the midst or in the middle of the garden.

12:43.897 --> 12:47.361
That's what she responds to the snake with, which is incorrect.

12:47.742 --> 12:48.082
Why?

12:48.738 --> 12:55.447
Because the tree of the knowledge of good and evil, according to God's estimation, is not in the middle of the garden.

12:57.310 --> 13:01.696
God has said that the tree of life is in the middle of the garden.

13:02.937 --> 13:11.149
The tree of the knowledge of good and evil is nearby, but God distinctly identifies the tree of life as the middle of his garden.

13:11.189 --> 13:16.596
But for Eve, the tree of the knowledge of good and evil is the center of her garden.

13:16.616 --> 13:17.938
It's the middle of her

13:18.370 --> 13:18.911
affection.

13:19.191 --> 13:22.296
It is the orbit around all of her attention.

13:22.817 --> 13:23.618
Why is that?

13:24.820 --> 13:26.983
Well, it tells us something really important about human nature.

13:28.004 --> 13:31.610
We are so very quick to forget all that God has given.

13:33.613 --> 13:36.797
And we are so very quick to focus on all that he hasn't.

13:37.979 --> 13:38.700
Don't we do this?

13:39.501 --> 13:43.607
Don't we focus on what we don't have as opposed to what we do have?

13:45.310 --> 13:48.114
Got a great job, but I don't have a boyfriend or a girlfriend.

13:48.738 --> 13:51.843
Man, I got an amazing personality, but I hate my body.

13:52.584 --> 13:56.089
Man, I've got people that love me, support me, or cheer inform me, but they're not the right kind of people.

13:56.129 --> 13:57.691
I want to be with those people instead.

13:57.711 --> 13:58.612
Do you see how this works?

13:59.674 --> 14:00.615
Figure it out for yourself.

14:00.675 --> 14:01.617
We all do this.

14:01.697 --> 14:05.162
We all look at what we have and we identify it as insufficient.

14:05.563 --> 14:06.624
We want something else.

14:06.644 --> 14:08.106
We want something more.

14:08.266 --> 14:10.770
And I think, and that's important, I think this.

14:10.970 --> 14:16.178
I don't actually see this clearly from the text because it doesn't tell us explicitly, but I do think.

14:16.610 --> 14:33.886
that what we get an eye into from this specific moment as Eve has centered her attention on the tree of the knowledge of good and evil as being in the middle of her garden, what we see is a heart of ingratitude springing up, which is the root, the first step to all sin.

14:35.067 --> 14:42.134
It's an ungrateful heart, which begs the question, where in your heart are you ungrateful for what God has given?

14:42.935 --> 14:46.418
The second thing that we see her say, which helps us to understand that

14:46.626 --> 14:51.332
Man, she is actually forgetting God's word, and she says, neither shall you touch it.

14:52.394 --> 14:54.877
Which isn't just a misunderstanding of what God has said.

14:55.418 --> 14:58.021
It's actually not even included in God's command.

14:58.081 --> 14:59.082
God never said that.

14:59.423 --> 15:02.547
It's an addition that she adds on to what God has said.

15:03.008 --> 15:14.002
It's interesting, when you read through the Bible, the Pharisees, which were the religious leaders of Jesus' day, those guys who were most biblically informed, they were the ones that were notoriously bad at this.

15:14.274 --> 15:17.959
They were horrible about adding things on to God's word.

15:17.979 --> 15:20.964
They actually rabbinnically had these things known as fence laws.

15:21.064 --> 15:29.216
Fence laws, there were hundreds, if not thousands, of these laws that served to protect them from going too far, disobeying God's word.

15:29.536 --> 15:31.119
And yet for fear going too far, you know what they did?

15:31.139 --> 15:32.100
They never went far enough.

15:33.562 --> 15:38.610
Too often, this happens to Christians, particularly good Christians.

15:38.690 --> 15:41.714
We find ourselves for fear of going too far,

15:41.794 --> 15:45.139
going far enough, we become a legalistic.

15:47.302 --> 15:51.248
We start thinking about what we do and what we don't do as opposed to what God has done.

15:51.288 --> 15:53.832
And as a result, you know what it does?

15:54.253 --> 16:01.905
It evokes within the spirit of a person this deep fear of losing this life that I have as opposed to enjoying the life that God has come to give.

16:04.188 --> 16:05.690
These are Eve's two mistakes.

16:06.452 --> 16:08.555
She has fallen prey to a very dangerous trap.

16:08.575 --> 16:09.436
You want to know what the trap is?

16:09.456 --> 16:10.738
The trap is she knows

16:10.818 --> 16:16.505
just enough about God, which is something we so very often fall into ourselves.

16:18.006 --> 16:32.463
Like, we know enough about God to believe in Him, to claim the identity of Christian, but we don't know enough about Jesus to know what we actually believe, to actually articulate the gospel.

16:34.025 --> 16:38.770
We know enough about God to love Him, but we don't know enough about God

16:39.714 --> 16:49.847
to give all of our life to Him, to surrender our every affection, to make sure that there's no part of us that's divided in any other place but is totally united in loving Him and Him alone.

16:50.889 --> 17:03.826
We know enough about God to trust Him, but we don't know enough about God to surrender every single inch of our life.

17:04.418 --> 17:10.988
There are things we hold back, pieces of ourselves we don't want him to touch, because though we say we do, we don't actually trust him.

17:11.268 --> 17:21.804
We know just enough about God to be dangerous at this whole Christian thing, but we don't know enough about God to keep ourselves from being in danger to ourselves.

17:24.267 --> 17:34.162
Psalm 119, verse nine, it says this, how can a young man or woman keep their way pure by guarding it

17:34.498 --> 17:35.960
according to what, to your word?

17:36.842 --> 17:39.485
With my whole heart, I seek you.

17:39.886 --> 17:41.529
Let me not wander from your commandments.

17:41.609 --> 17:44.833
I've stored up your word in my heart that I might not sin against you.

17:44.874 --> 17:45.454
Do you hear it?

17:46.175 --> 17:50.983
That kind of ferocious faith that depends wholeheartedly on the words of God?

17:51.023 --> 17:54.728
So let me ask you something, because I think that this is a helpful litmus test.

17:55.009 --> 18:03.922
Whenever your life goes sideways, whenever things just kind of fall off the normal path and things become very, very difficult, what comes out of you?

18:04.962 --> 18:08.167
Like whenever you get fired unexpectedly, what's your natural response?

18:08.187 --> 18:15.818
Whenever that guy whom you've been dating for years at this point breaks up with you instead of going into marriage with you, what comes out of you?

18:15.858 --> 18:23.790
Whenever you find some loved one, a family member, a dear friend comes down with some sort of fatal diagnosis, what comes out of you?

18:28.497 --> 18:29.458
Jesus faced.

18:33.794 --> 18:37.439
The three most pressure-packed moments in his story.

18:41.304 --> 18:50.255
Tempted in the wilderness before he began his ministry, Garden of Gethsemane, the night of his arrest, and Calvary dying for the sins of the world.

18:50.896 --> 18:52.398
And you want to know what came out of him?

18:54.661 --> 18:55.281
The words of God.

18:57.744 --> 19:02.130
Virtually every single word he spoke

19:02.242 --> 19:04.906
in those moments that were most pressure packed.

19:07.931 --> 19:09.113
They were God's words.

19:12.158 --> 19:12.419
Why?

19:15.724 --> 19:18.028
Not because he's just trying to fulfill prophecy.

19:19.631 --> 19:20.171
He does that.

19:20.472 --> 19:21.033
That's true.

19:21.393 --> 19:24.178
He does fulfill prophecy in the process.

19:24.546 --> 19:27.190
of saying these things amidst these difficulties.

19:27.210 --> 19:28.351
But that's not why he does it.

19:28.411 --> 19:28.912
He does it.

19:28.932 --> 19:29.953
He speaks these things.

19:30.134 --> 19:32.877
Because out of the overflow of the heart, guess what?

19:33.118 --> 19:34.419
The mouth is gonna speak.

19:35.681 --> 19:39.206
